(:kind :chapter :book "Lacuna Labs Doc" :chapter-number null :title "Sakura Scheme — Language Burndown Plan" :source-path "/Users/alfred/code/lacuna-labs/burndown/sakura-scheme-lang-burndown-plan-2026-07-13.md" :size 10232 :sha256 "1b0e85ea48b70c71" :content "# Sakura Scheme — Language Burndown Plan\n\n**Written:** 2026-07-13\n**Owner:** Alfred + Claude (personally)\n**Source memory:** `project_lang_notes_2026_07_13.md` (notes 1-10)\n**Status:** Ready to push to burndown\n\n---\n\n## Mission\n\nShip **Sakura Scheme** as the complete working runtime — fantasy console + AI + commercial shop verbs, everything wired, everything callable. Do the whole stack first. Figure out how to block down to lower tiers (Jesse Scheme, Lacuna Engineering) later.\n\nAlfred's directive: *\"Let's work on Sakura Scheme first, and we will decide how it pops up to the top... Let's not worry about blocking it off because that's not our problem right now.\"*\n\n---\n\n## Architecture recap (from lang notes)\n\nFive layers, one language:\n\n| Layer | Content | Loads by default |\n|---|---|---|\n| **L0 CORE** | R7RS Scheme, macros, reader, interp, base primitives | Everyone always |\n| **L1 MEDIA** | Framebuffer + drawing + sound + animation + input, adapter-based | scheme-lang default binary + Sakura Scheme + Jesse |\n| **L2 AI** | Cortex, LLM primitives, retrieval | Sakura Scheme, anyone with AI runtime |\n| **L3 GAME** | Sprites, collisions, physics, tile maps | Sakura Scheme (fantasy console) |\n| **L4 COMMERCIAL** | shop verbs (etsy/*, ebay/*, shopify/*, meta/*, google/*), auth-gated | Sakura Scheme + Curator consumer |\n\n**The reference manual IS the language** — `~/code/scheme-lang/docs/SAKURA-SCHEME-REFERENCE.slat` (1,157 verbs + 70 core forms). Everything derives from it.\n\n**Carts live separately** at `~/code/scheme-carts/` — 10,762 .sks + 10,755 .md + broken/. Language points at cart directory via `scheme-lang.config.slat`. Slug-pairing (filename stem), no ML at ingestion.\n\n---\n\n## Phases\n\n### Phase 1 — Framebuffer + Drawing (L1)\n\n- `src/framebuffer.js` — core pixel buffer, drawing math, no output format\n- Configurable modes: `(set-mode 80 80)` default · `(set-mode 128 128)` PICO-8 · `(set-mode 240 136)` TIC-80\n- Drawing verbs honor args as grid coordinates (circle already fixed tonight)\n- **Fix `line` and `rect` — same auto-scale bug as circle**\n- Adapter split: `dots-adapter.js` (rename from braille per Alfred's \"dots\" directive), `iterm-adapter.js`, `kitty-adapter.js`, `sixel-adapter.js`, `browser-canvas-adapter.js`\n- Color palette: 16-color indexed OR free RGBA per mode\n\n### Phase 2 — Sound (L1)\n\n- Sound API: `(tone freq dur)` · `(note \"A4\" 0.5)` · `(sfx ...)` · `(music ...)` · `(silence dur)`\n- Adapters: Web Audio (browser), `node-speaker` (terminal), terminal-bell fallback\n- Shared frame timing with drawing (same `on-frame` loop)\n\n### Phase 3 — Animation + Input (L1)\n\n- `(on-frame handler)` — 60fps loop\n- `(sync)` — yield to event loop\n- `(sleep sec)`\n- Input events: keyboard/mouse/gamepad wired through REPL non-line mode\n- `(save-cart \"mygame.sks\")` / `(load-cart)` — cart-shaped save\n\n### Phase 4 — SLAT Reference Loader + ALL VERBS WORK (L0 + implementation completeness)\n\n**Alfred directive 2026-07-13:** *\"We have over a thousand verbs. Just make them all work. Test them. Jesse doesn't like bullshit.\"*\n\n- Read `SAKURA-SCHEME-REFERENCE.slat` at startup\n- For each verb entry: find JS impl, register with metadata (arity, contract, examples, metering)\n- **NO stub-and-defer.** Every verb in the reference gets a working implementation. If it can't work standalone (needs Cortex, needs a shop, needs auth), it errors CLEANLY with a helpful message — not \"not implemented.\"\n- **Test every verb.** Auto-generated test per verb from the reference's `examples` field. Novice/intermediate/expert example each becomes a test case. If a verb's own reference example doesn't run, the CI fails.\n- **Reverse check:** JS impls without SLAT entries warn at startup\n- Reference wins when they disagree (per \"reference IS the language\" doctrine)\n- **Deep bugs OK, superficial bugs NOT.** If we're going to leave a bug, it's a genuinely interesting one Jesse would enjoy finding — not \"circle doesn't take its argument\" surface-level trash.\n\n**This is the largest phase.** ~1,227 verbs × implementation + test = real work. But it's what \"make them all work\" costs, and it's what makes the language shippable to someone like Jesse who won't tolerate bullshit.\n\n### Phase 5 — Game (L3) — physics, collisions, sprites\n\n- Extract Curator's collision + physics code as portable module (or interface + adapter — decide after quick audit)\n- Standalone default: simple AABB collision + basic verlet physics\n- Adapter override: Curator's fancier engine when running inside HelloSurface\n- Sprites, tile maps, basic entity system\n\n### Phase 6 — AI (L2) — Cortex + LLM primitives\n\n- Interface defined in scheme-lang; implementation provided by consumer runtime\n- `(cortex/remember key value)` · `(cortex/recall key)` · `(cortex/query pattern)`\n- LLM primitives as stubs — real impls arrive from Sakura runtime / Curator / Lacuna\n- Configurable model routing\n\n### Phase 7 — Commercial Verbs (L4)\n\n- Register all shop verbs from reference (etsy/*, ebay/*, shopify/*, meta/*, google/*) with `:cost 'external-api-call` metadata\n- **Dispatcher hook** — before invoking a paid verb: check auth + quota\n  - No auth → clean error: *\"sign in to use `etsy/publish-listing` — run `sakura login`\"*\n  - Present but blocked. Not blocked from AUTHORING scripts. Blocked at EXECUTION.\n- Auth token pulled from Cortex on demand\n\n### Phase 8 — CLI Login\n\n- `sakura login` command — Google OAuth device-flow (works from terminal, no browser roundtrip needed)\n- Stores token in Cortex keyed to operator\n- Runtime pulls transparently when paid verbs fire\n- Other providers (Apple, GitHub) can be added later; Google first because most operators already have it\n\n### Phase 9 — Book of Jesse (~50-page onboarding MD)\n\n- Audience: **someone who uses Fennel + TIC-80 + Clojure + Lua** (Alfred's friend Jesse)\n- Framing: *\"Alfred knows you use Clojure, Lua, Fennel, TIC-80. He wanted to make sure you were covered. Here's how this works.\"*\n- Intro: download, install, first REPL, `(circle 40 40 15)`\n- **Five-layer walkthrough** with concrete examples per layer\n- **Fantasy console section:** build a small playable game (starting with a bouncing ball, ending with something that could ship)\n- SLAT explained — what it is, why it matters, how to write animations with it\n- **Fennel/TIC-80/Clojure pattern-equivalents** — how what Jesse already knows translates:\n  - Fennel destructuring ↔ Sakura Scheme's destructuring\n  - TIC-80 `cls`/`circ`/`spr` ↔ Sakura's `(clear)`/`(circle)`/`(sprite)`\n  - Clojure threading macros ↔ Sakura's macro system\n  - Lua tables ↔ Sakura hash-tables\n- Common headaches + solutions (from real Fennel/TIC-80 patterns)\n- Sample projects (small, ambitious enough to feel real)\n- Ships on GitHub next to the language as `docs/BOOK-OF-JESSE.md`\n- **50 pages substantive** — not a marketing intro, real teaching prose\n\n### Phase 10 — Testing + Docs + Ship\n\n- End-to-end tests: REPL boot → SLAT load → verb call → adapter render\n- `sakura test` runs the suite\n- Rendered docs site (VitePress build reads SLAT reference)\n- GitHub Pages update\n- `npm publish` for `sakura-scheme` and `scheme-lang`\n\n---\n\n## Sequencing recommendation\n\n**Do NOT dispatch in parallel. Do this personally, in order:**\n\n1. Phase 1 (framebuffer + line/rect fix) — foundational, unblocks everything else\n2. Phase 4 (SLAT loader) — makes 1,227 verbs callable\n3. Phase 2 + 3 (sound + animation + input) — L1 complete\n4. Phase 5 (game/physics) — L3 partial\n5. Phase 6 (AI stubs) — L2 partial\n6. Phase 7 (commercial + gating) — L4 wired, gated\n7. Phase 8 (login) — unlocks L4 for signed-in users\n8. Phase 9 (Book of Jesse) — the gift + the onboarding\n9. Phase 10 (test + ship)\n\n---\n\n## Estimates\n\n- Phase 1: 4-6 hrs\n- Phase 2: 3-4 hrs\n- Phase 3: 3-4 hrs\n- Phase 4: 4-6 hrs\n- Phase 5: 6-10 hrs\n- Phase 6: 4-6 hrs (interface only; impls come from consumer)\n- Phase 7: 4-6 hrs\n- Phase 8: 3-5 hrs\n- Phase 9: 12-20 hrs (real prose, 50 pages substantive)\n- Phase 10: 4-6 hrs\n\n**Total: ~45-75 hours focused work.** Roughly 1-2 weeks depending on interrupts.\n\n---\n\n## Doctrine compliance (all apply)\n\n- Reference manual IS the language (code derives from it, never other way)\n- Familiarity-not-knowledge for what she says about her own tech\n- Publishable prose for Book of Jesse (SICP-bar, kid-readable, warm framing)\n- No hallucination (real Fennel/TIC-80 patterns, real Clojure translations)\n- No corporate name-drops in Book of Jesse\n- SLAT format for language artifacts; MD OK for Book of Jesse (gift + prose format)\n- The kid at the other end sits under everything (Book of Jesse IS that kid — grown, but same shape)\n- Delicacy doctrine\n\n---\n\n## What Alfred and Claude decide together (not delegated)\n\n- Framebuffer refactor\n- SLAT loader design\n- Book of Jesse authoring (Claude personally, per Alfred's earlier \"you're gonna do that personally\")\n- Auth flow shape (Google OAuth device-flow specifics)\n- Verb metering rules\n\n## What gets dispatched (parallel, non-blocking)\n\n- Word-books knowledge expansion plan (agent in flight — task #124)\n- Films/scenes plan landed already (v2 amendments to fold in)\n- Docs burndown queue (reminder queued for after lang, task #119)\n\n---\n\n## Reference locations\n\n- Language: `~/code/scheme-lang/`\n- Reference SLAT: `~/code/scheme-lang/docs/SAKURA-SCHEME-REFERENCE.slat`\n- Config: `~/code/scheme-lang/scheme-lang.config.slat`\n- Carts: `~/code/scheme-carts/`\n- This plan: `~/code/lacuna-labs/burndown/sakura-scheme-lang-burndown-plan-2026-07-13.md`\n\n---\n\n## Note on the tier-strip-down (Alfred's later concern)\n\nOnce Sakura Scheme (full stack L0-L4) works end-to-end, the strip-down to lower binaries becomes a config-file exercise, not a re-architecture:\n\n- **Jesse's install** = `scheme-lang` binary with `:layers '(core media)` in config → loads L0+L1 only\n- **Lacuna Engineering** = `scheme-lang` binary with `:layers '(core ai telemetry)` → L0+L2+eng\n- **Sakura Scheme** = default `sakura-scheme` binary, all layers\n- **Curator inside HelloSurface** = same binary as Sakura Scheme with adapter overrides for L3 physics\n\nThat configuration decision waits until L0-L4 is proven working.\n")
